to di&s;engage this billet from the author's hand,
the &s;orrowing female fell on her knees, entreating
him to de&s;i&s;t, and telling him, &s;he had promi&s;ed,
upon oath, to communicate the contents to no
per&s;on upon earth, but to carry the letter, upon
<PB N="294" REF="295">
her husband's decea&s;e, to the gentleman to who&s;e
care it was directed.</P>
<P>Renaldo a&s;&s;ured her upon his honour, that he
was the very Renaldo count de Melvile for
whom it was intended; and the young crea|ture
was &s;o much confounded at this informa|tion,
that before &s;he could recollect her&s;elf,
Melvile had opened the billet and read the&s;e
words. &startq;If this paper &s;hould fall into the hands
of the noble Renaldo, he will under&s;tand that
Fathom was the mo&s;t execrable traitor that ever
