<P>The&s;e charitable &s;teps being taken, Count de
Melvile intreated the apothecary's &s;ervant to
procure a tent bed for the accommodation of
the &s;ick per&s;on, with all imaginable di&s;patch;
<PB N="296" REF="297">
and in le&s;s than an hour, one was actually pitch|ed,
and Fathom lifted into it, after he had
been &s;hifted and in &s;ome mea&s;ure purified from
the dregs of his indigence. During this tran&s;|action
the ladies were conducted to a tavern
not far off, where dinner was be&s;poke, that
they might be at hand to &s;ee the effect of their
