with the nature of my misfortune. So
<PB N="298" REF="299">
much &s;ympathy and good &s;en&s;e appeared in his
deportment and conver&s;ation, that I gratified his
reque&s;t, and he, in return for my confidence,
&s;aved me from the mo&s;t horrible part of my
pro&s;pect, by taking me into his protection, and
re&s;erving me for his own appetite. In this &s;itu|ation
I lived a whole year, until I was deprived
of my keeper by an apoplectic fit, and turned
out of doors by his relations, who did not, how|ever,
&s;trip me of the cloaths and moveables,
which I owed to his bounty. Far from being
as yet reconciled to a vitious life, I re&s;olved to
