my wrongs. Wretched as he then was, I re|membered
the accompli&s;hed youth who had cap|tivated
my virgin heart, the old impre&s;&s;ions &s;till
remained, I &s;aw his penitence, pitied his mis|fortune;
and his wife being dead, con&s;ented to
join his fate, the ceremony having been per|formed
by a fellow pri&s;oner, who was in or|ders.
Though his hard-hearted creditor had no
other chance of being payed, than that of &s;et|ting
him at liberty, he lent a deaf ear to all our
&s;upplications; and this cruelty con&s;piring with the
angui&s;h of my hu&s;band's own reflection, affected
